The '''April 6-8, 2006 Tornado Outbreak''' was a major [[tornado outbreak]] in the [[Central United States|Central]] and parts of the [[Southern United States]] that began on April 6, 2006 in the [[Great Plains]] and continued until April 8 in [[South Carolina]], with most of the activity on April 7. The hardest-hit area was [[Middle Tennessee]] where several strong tornadoes devastated entire neighborhoods and left nine people dead. The worst damage took place in [[Gallatin, Tennessee]]. Other communities north of [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] were also hard hit. 

There were 73 tornadoes confirmed across 13 states, with the bulk of them coming on the afternoon and evening of April 7 across the South, particularly in [[Tennessee]]. In total, 13 deaths were reported as a result of the severe weather (12 of them in Tennessee) and over $1.5&nbsp;billion in damage was reported,<ref name="billiondollar"/> of which over $630&nbsp;million was in Middle Tennessee.<ref name="linger">{{cite news| url=http://www.gallatinnewsexaminer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20061007/COUNTY08/610070334 |title=Storms' losses linger |publisher=Gallatin News-Examiner |date=2006-10-07 |accessdate=2006-11-11}}</ref> It was the third major outbreak of 2006, hot on the heels of [[April 2, 2006 Tornado Outbreak|a major outbreak]] on April 2. It was also considered to be the worst disaster event in Middle Tennessee since the [[1998 Nashville tornado outbreak|Nashville tornado outbreak]] on April 16, 1998.

==Meteorological synopsis==
[[Image:SPC severe outlook 04072006.png|thumb|left|[[probability|Probabilistic]] maps issued by the [[Storm Prediction Center]] during the heart of the outbreak.]]The outbreak took place as a result of a powerful [[Low pressure area|low pressure system]] over the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] that produced a strong [[cold front]] which tracked eastward across the South.  The dry, cold air behind the cold front combined with warm, humid air from the [[Gulf of Mexico]] to allow severe thunderstorms to form, particularly on April 7.<ref>{{cite web  | last = Konop  | first = Elizabeth  | title = April 7, 2006 Tornado Outbreak across the Tennessee Valley  | publisher = [[University of Wisconsin]]  | date = May 10, 2006  | url = http://www.aos.wisc.edu/uwaosjournal/Volume1/AOS453/FCS_Konop.pdf  | format = pdf  | accessdate = 2008-03-13}}</ref>

The [[Storm Prediction Center]] issued a high risk for severe weather for both April 6 and April 7 in the areas likely to be affected. Conditions were favorable for an extremely strong tornado outbreak on both days.<ref>{{cite web  | title = Apr 6, 2006 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook   | publisher = [[Storm Prediction Center]]  | date = April 6, 2006  | url = http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2006/day1otlk_20060406_1630.html  | accessdate = 2008-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | title = Apr 7, 2006 1630 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook   | publisher = [[Storm Prediction Center]]  | date = April 7, 2006  | url = http://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2006/day1otlk_20060407_1630.html  | accessdate = 2008-03-12}}</ref>

Activity was not as great as expected on April 6, with only 12 tornadoes confirmed, mostly in [[Kansas]].<ref>{{cite web  | title = April 6, 2006 tornadoes  | publisher = Tornado History Project  | url = http://www.tornadohistoryproject.com/tornado.php?p=1&s=4&d=asc&yr=2006&mo=4&day=6&st=%&fu=%&co=Any&l=500&format=basic&submit=Table&dcom=&dpho=&dvid=&ddat=on&dtim=&dsta=on&dfuj=on&dfat=on&dinj=on&dwid=&dlen=&dcou=on&dong=&dare=&dfar=&drot=&ddam=&dpl=&dpw=&dtyp=&drem=&dtlat=&dtlon=&dllat=&dllon=&dstt=&dtor=  | accessdate = 2008-03-13}}</ref> Several of the tornadoes were damaging, but no fatalities and only a few injuries were reported. The reason for the relatively modest activity was due to the more stable than expected air mass that day over the region, with lower [[dewpoint]]s and less [[wind shear]] despite the absence of a cap which would have otherwise allowed a massive outbreak.<ref name="HighRisk">{{cite web| url=http://sphs.angeltowns.net/A_R_Wehrle/recenthighrisk2.html|title=SPC High Risk Forecasts May 24, 2004-Present |publisher=Stoughton Piston Head Society |date=2006-04-07|accessdate=2006-11-12}}</ref>

